messages.text: They have rifles slung across their backs.
One just fired in the air with a handgun.
Retaliation for massive drug sweeps we did last year.
We arrested dozens of people, including their boss.
It was all over the news.
We need to try to get you out of there without them seeing you.
Do you see any numbers painted on the walls?
Allison see’s numbers painted on the far wall.
That section of track has been out of commission since the hurricane.
OK. I want you to head in the opposite direction.
Allison leaves the alcove and limps toward the entrance of the tunnel.
My ankle still hurts. It’s throbbing.
She grimaces in pain, and finds a crate to hide behind.
OK, rest for a few seconds.
They’re detonating them in a secure area.
Don’t I have a right to know?
Jake should have stayed with you.
But he doesn’t know how to turn off his police scanner.
He decided to show up even though he has a sprained shoulder.
He wanted to make sure you were safe.
I can’t believe he did all this for me.
No. He wasn’t even supposed to be here.
Allison. I just heard from Jake.
Allison stands and looks around to make sure it’s clear.
Allison struggles to put distance between herself and the Russian terrorists.
I’m near the area where Jake told me to climb down.
I want you to find another safe spot.
A couple of doors on this side.
Should I climb back up to the platform?
Let Jake secure the area first.
Pick a place along the wall, away from the lights.
Make yourself as small as possible.
